        "content": "<p>There is a <a href=\"https://proofassistants.stackexchange.com/q/4626/122\">PA.SX question about infinite turning machines and if it matters to define them universe polymorphically.</a>  While it is probably good to define them that way, it also probably doesn't matter since they either halt before <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>ω</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\omega_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5806em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> or don't halt at all.  <em>But is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>ω</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\omega_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5806em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> the same between universes?</em>  I think this comes down to a few questions about <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Ordinal.omega#doc\">docs#Ordinal.omega</a> including if the following theorem is true:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">lift_omega0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I don't see it in Mathlib, but I assume it is true and just follows from <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Ordinal.lift_lift#doc\">docs#Ordinal.lift_lift</a> if used correctly, right?</p>",
        "id": 494371808,
        "sender_full_name": "Jason Rute",
        "timestamp": 1737123781
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And I guess one also needs to know that there aren't any new ordinals added beneath <code>Ordinal.omega 1</code> after lifting.  But this is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Ordinal.lt_lift_iff#doc\">docs#Ordinal.lt_lift_iff</a> right?</p>",
        "id": 494372870,
        "sender_full_name": "Jason Rute",
        "timestamp": 1737124095
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually, there is an X thread between Joel David Hamkins and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"345260\">@Andrej Bauer</span> that suggests maybe this is not true? <a href=\"https://x.com/JDHamkins/status/1880190691147456525\">https://x.com/JDHamkins/status/1880190691147456525</a></p>",
        "id": 494374533,
        "sender_full_name": "Jason Rute",
        "timestamp": 1737124577
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Try rewriting on <code>Ordinal.lift_omega</code>, then <code>Ordinal.lift_one</code></p>",
        "id": 494382679,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1737127079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">lift_omega1</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">max</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">calc</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift_omega</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift_one</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 494450195,
        "sender_full_name": "Jason Rute",
        "timestamp": 1737152425
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"115715\">Jason Rute</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Countable.20.28or.20omega1.29.20is.20the.20same.20when.20lifted/near/494371808\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think this comes down to a few questions about <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Ordinal.omega#doc\">docs#Ordinal.omega</a> including if the following theorem is true:</p>\n<p><div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">lift_omega0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lift</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Ordinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">omega</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div><br>\n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If <code>simp</code> can't solve this then something is wrong</p>",
